Notes on Data sets and Organization:

Through separate rounds of cleaning and duplicate removal, georeferencing, obtaining climate data, and (soon) scoring, there are several different csv files with Nemophila specimen data present in this project repository. For clarity, they are listed out her detailing what they contain and how recently they were made.

Specimen Records:
These csv files can be found in the data_cleaning folder. They include

CCH1 Data:
- Nemo_CCH1_02182020.csv - CCH1 data set standardized by Ivana
- nemo_cch1_cleaned.csv - cleaned (by DG) CCH1 data set - Georeferenced CCH1 splits (folder) - split by herbarium and georeferenced; combined with CCH2 data

CCH2 Data:
- occurrences.csv - the original specimen data downloaded from CCH2
- nemo_cch2_Dec2019.csv - cleaned up from the occurrences data
- nemo_cch2_cleaned_V2.csv - further cleaning, removing duplicates. This was then split up into subsets by herbarium for georeferencing & scoring.
- Splits for PI folder has most recent cleaned CCH2 splits ("_pi.csv" files are more up to date! Dupes & odd things removed, data re-split by CCH2 herbaria after running combine_cch1_cch2_V2.R script)

Combined CCH1 & CCH2:
* See combine_cch1_cch2_V2.R for more details.
- cch1&2_combined.csv - attempt at combination, NOT cleaned
- nemo_all_1.csv - first updated combination of CCH1 and CCH2 records
- nemo_all_2.csv - second combination of CCH1 and CCH2 records, added elevation (m) from elevatr package. (Used to make latest PI splits). Most up-to-date combined specimen data!!

Climate Data:
See get_cna_all.Rmd for more details. Uses nemo_all_2.csv as input to create ClimateNA compatible csv all_CNA_s.csv.
- First-attempt CCH1 and 2 climate data can be found in their respective folders under ClimateNA
- ClimateNA downloads are in the cna_rawfiles folder, in the all_CNA folder under
- These were cleaned and combined to get norms_raw_51_and_81.csv, YoC_Y_and_L1.csv, 100y_avg.csv
- Anomalies calculated in get_cna_anoms.Rmd, creates climNA_anoms.csv
- All the above data sets combined into climNA_nemo_all.csv saved in all_cna folder Most up-to-date Climate-only data!!

Combined data sets:
In this Rmd, nemo_all_2.csv, with added error distance, and climNA_nemo_all.csv, with PPT vars. log-transformed, are combined and saved to nemo_full_1901_2019.csv, filtering for years only from 1901-2019. Most up-to-date combined file!!

Create subset of data where each observation has an error distance:

#Filter specimens to those collected after 1900
nemo_df2 <- nemo_df1 %>% 
  filter(year >= 1901) #1677 obs

nemo_all_errors <- nemo_df2 %>% 
  filter(!is.na(error_dist_m)) 
#1239 out of 1764 obs with error distance
#1166 after rm records before 1901

#0-5 km resolution
nemo_e0_5 <- nemo_all_errors %>% 
  filter(error_bin == "<2 km" | error_bin == "2-5 km") #1081 entries

#0-4 km
nemo_e0_4 <-  nemo_all_errors %>% 
  filter(error_dist_m >= 0 & error_dist_m <= 4000) #1010 obs #Do Not include error_bin in models

#0-2 km
nemo_e2 <- nemo_all_errors %>% 
  filter(error_bin == "<2 km") #761 obs

A combined data set (nemo_df2) is saved within Climate_1.Rmd and titled nemo_full_1901_2019.csv

Variable Correlations:

Which geographical and climate variables are correlated with one another?
(And how could these make future analyses difficult?)

Correlations to be wary of:
[Geographic]
- Lat correlated with MAT, DD5, AHM (~-.3-.4 ), elev_m (-.4), AHM (-.6), MAP (.58)
- Long correlated with CMD, AHM, MWMT (.4-.5), elev (.51), MAP (-.57)
- Elev_m also correlated to MAT (-.47) [but not MAP], MCMT, NFFD (~-.6), DD_0 (.68), MSP, PAS (.44)

[Climatic]
- MAT with MAP/MSP (.59), DD5 (~1), DD_0 (-.76), CMD:NFFD (.6-.7), PAS (.62)
- MAP also with DD5 (.62), AHM (.9)
- Anomalies: Some variables negatively correlated b/w _Y and _As

  • Seasonal temperature variables correlated with each other, with elevation
  • Some Spring Tave and Spring PPT parameters correlated
  • Seasonal PPT correlated with DD5, Spring temperatures, not correlated to elevation
  • Lat and Long similarly correlated to MAT [+/-0.32] and MAP [+/- 0.57], lat*long = 0.93
  • Anomalies pretty uncorrelated to other periods!

Year had no large correlations with any variables (all < .3). Normals strongly correlated from different periods - MAT x MAP correlations consistent.

Interactions:
- MAT_Y is greater at more inland longitudes, and at lower elevations
- MAT_Y declines faster going up in elevation with more inland longitudes. This effect is strengthened by greater MAP_Y (below 1000 m) in the west and weakened by greater MAP_Y in the east - Interactions with long are less significant than with elev_m and MAP

Effect of Error Distance on DOY ~ Climate models

The following analyses aim to measure the effect of different error distance on model outputs, specifically,

  • \(R^2\) values
  • Parameter estimates and
  • significance of climate variables in their effect on DOY

For 100 year averages for MAT, MAP, Tmin_sp, Tave_sp, PPT_sp, PPT_wt

Including error distance (or error bin) as a covariate shows no model improvement. Though the smallest bin, 0-2 km error, has a significant effect in the model, none of the parameter estimates of the bins are significantly different from one another.

In Summary

Filtering out larger error_bins led to no real improvements in model \(R^2\)s, though of the subsets the 0-5 group often had better \(R^2\)s. Based on confidence intervals, there are no significant differences in parameter estiamtes between data including all observations and data including less uncertain coordinate estimates.

Using data from more precise error distances led to increases in parameter estimate varaition (SE), especially for 0-2 km.

Lack of improvements may be due to loss of meaningful variation from records with greater uncertainty. Also, looking only at records with any error distance, there is a reduction in \(R^2\) values.

[From old models]
> Including error bin as a covariate (for models with 2+ bins) slightly increases \(R^2\) but not parameter estimate (by much). For this reason, and the fact that uncertainty should have no direct effect on DOY, Ive removed it. The significant effect of 2-5 km bin for error distance on DOY - slightly earlier - is likely due to chance.

Filtering out records with larger error distances generally improves models, but improvements seem greatest for MAT, Tmin and Tave. MAP, PPT_wt, and PPT_sp models had larger parameter estimates for 0-2 km errors but Filtering finely to records with 0-2 km error led to larger parameter estimates, but at the cost of reduced R2 values and much larger SE. This could be due to a loss of variation and represents a trade-off to consider with future models. Oddly, a couple models with errors from 0-4 km were worse (for MAT, Tave_sp) than 0-2 or 0-5 error models. Model improvements were persistent when the error_bin covariate was removed from models, though R2 values were very slightly reduced.

In future models,
- Consider treating error distance as a random effect? - Consider comparing all data with those with errors from 0-5 km

Note2: It is not necessary to include covariates for elev_m, lat/long, year if were mainly interested in the effect of climate variables on DOY

Delaying effect of PPT observable in wt, sp, and sm. Model with spring PPT has highest \(R^2\) and a higher parameter estimate than that of winter PPT. The estimate for the summer PPT model is quite large, but has a low R2.


In Summary

DOY is sensitive to both MAT (advancing effect) and MAP (delaying effect) over 100 years, and precipitation may be just as stronger, or even stronger, than MAT.

Spring temperatures (particularly Tave and also Tmin) explain more variation and have larger estimates in their relationship with DOY than winter temperatures.

Precipitation has the strongest effect on DOY for spring, followed by winter, averages. Summer PPT had a large paramter estimate but the model R2 was much lower.
